DAYBOOK MEXICO: Central Bank Reserves, Wal-Mart de Mexico Sales

-- B y   J o s e   E n r i q u e   A r r i o j a
-- 
2011-09-06T05:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-06/daybook-mexico-central-bank-reserves-wal-mart-de-mexico-sales.html
Mexico ’s central bank releases its
weekly report on international reserves and Wal-Mart de Mexico,
 Latin America ’s largest retailer, reports same-store sales for
the month of August.  WHAT TO WATCH:  *Banco de Mexico publishes  international reserves  for the week
ended Sept. 2. The nation’s reserves rose to a record $136.8
billion in the week ended Aug. 26, the nation’s central bank
reported last week on its website. Banxico, as the bank is
known, releases the report at 9 a.m. Mexico City time.  *Wal-Mart de Mexico, Latin America’s largest retailer, reports
same-store sales for the month of August. Same-store sales rose
3.9 percent in July and total sales for Mexico and Central
America were 30.9 billion pesos, the company reported Aug. 8.  MARKETS:  *The Mexican IPC fell 3.6 percent, the biggest drop since Aug.
8, to 33,880.02.  *The yield on Mexico’s benchmark peso-denominated bond due in
2024 rose 8 basis points, or 0.08 percentage point, to 6.29
percent, according to Banco Santander SA data. The price of the
security fell 0.87 centavo to 133.32 centavos per peso.  *The peso fell 1 percent to 12.5373 per  U.S. dollar  from 12.4079
on Sept. 2, to the weakest level in more than three weeks
against the U.S. dollar amid concern the European debt crisis
may worsen. The currency has lost 1.6 percent this year, the
second-worst performance among major Latin American currencies
tracked by Bloomberg after  Argentina ’s peso.  EQUITIES  *Retailers: Mexico’s consumer confidence index fell to 93.4 in
August from 95.5 in July, the national statistics agency
reported yesterday on its website. Economists estimated a
confidence reading of 94.3, according to the median of five
forecasts compiled by Bloomberg.  *El Puerto de Liverpool SAB (LIVEPOLC MM), a luxury-goods
retailer, dropped 3.9 percent to 89.55 pesos. Wal-Mart de Mexico
SAB retreated 4.5 percent to 31.12 pesos.  *U.S.-related companies:  Service industries  in the U.S. probably
expanded in August at the slowest pace in more than a year,
economists said before a report scheduled for today. The
 Institute for Supply Management ’s non-manufacturing index fell
to 51 last month, the lowest since January 2010, from 52.7 in
July, according to the median of 59 forecasts in a Bloomberg
News survey.  *Cemex SAB (CEMEXCPO MM), the largest cement maker in the
Americas, declined 3.2 percent to 6.11 pesos, the lowest closing
price since March 9, 2009. Alfa SAB (ALFAA MM), the world’s
largest producer of aluminum engine heads, fell 3.2 percent to
144.25 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jose Enrique Arrioja in Mexico City at 
